data.title: "Traditional" perhaps
data.text: Very nice owner. OK for families with kids perhaps; basic formica type tables and Mexican TV program: Found the food to be so-so. My friend had cheese enchiladas and I had the fajitas. There were no veggies to speak of nor any of the condiments I normally expect (e.g. no guacamole or sour cream). Large portion of rice and beans. The salad consisted of two leafs of lettuce. I wouldn't go again as the food wasn't worth the price.

data.title: Looking for a "hole in the wall" Taqueria in the Dallas suburbs?  This is it.
data.text:
DESCRIPTION
This looks like a husband and wife team opened up their living and dinning room into a small Taqueria.  The food is prepared fresh an on-site.  The tacos are my favorite.  Also, I'm not sure if the hot sauce is bottled, but I can't get enough of it.   It's a great place to go if you have a craving for some authentic, home cooked, Mexican Taqueria style food.

PROS
* Authentic home cooked Mexican Food
* Mom / Pop independent owners
* Can customer make anything for you upon request (i.e. grilled and diced Jalapenos)

CONS
* I always seem to walk out of there wondering why I spent so much on Taqueria food.  It's a little on the high side. ($15+) --- but I don't mind helping an independent restaurateur.

data.title: Hole in the wall Mexican spot; tasty enchiladas and tacos
data.text: This place is in an old house with maybe 8 tables and a small menu. Food is good and perfect for lunch or breakfast. Great tacos and good cheese enchiladas. Caldo was nice too.  Local place with friendly service. Stop by and see what you think.
